<paragraph blockId="5.[151,761,1464,2069]" lastBlockId="5.[828,1437,1372,2067]" pageId="5" pageNumber="262">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[181,300,2013,2037]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="262">Coloration</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[318,417,2014,2037]" captionStart="Figs 1–6. 1–2" captionStartId="3.[151,188,1998,2017]" captionTargetBox="[201,1387,195,1963]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[197,1390,189,1963]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 1–6. 1–2 – Concavifer marmoratus Dlabola, 1960: 1 – dorsal view of male; 2– dorsal view of female. 3–4 – Phlepsopsius arabicus Dlabola, 1979: 3 – dorsal view; 4 – head and thorax. 5–6 – Hishimonus phycitis (Distant, 1908): 5 – dorsal view; 6 – head and thorax." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3699262" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3699262/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="262">Figs 3–4</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[432,486,2014,2037]" captionStart="Figs 7–12. 7–8" captionStartId="4.[151,188,1414,1433]" captionTargetBox="[158,1432,193,1379]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,189,1382]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 7–12. 7–8 – Concavifer marmoratus Dlabola, 1960: 7 – lateral view; 8 – face. 9–10 – Phlepsopsius arabicus Dlabola, 1979: 9 – lateral view; 10 – face. 11–12 – Hishimonus phycitis (Distant, 1908): 11 – lateral view; 12– face." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3699264" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3699264/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="262">9–10</figureCitation>
). Ground colour greyish white with tinge of yellow, with some extremely dense brown mottling, particularly on forewings behind base. Face yellow. Vertex with two oblique V-shaped brown spots and two small spots laterally, posterior margin with three small spots. Pronotum yellowish brown, with pale area beyond vertex and incomplete rows of spots forming a net-like pattern. Forewings with brown spots in incomplete rows forming a net-like pattern. Legs yellow and mottled with brown, all spines arising from brown base. Legs with brown setal areolae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[828,1437,1372,2067]" pageId="5" pageNumber="262">
<emphasis box="[858,1037,1659,1683]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="262">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[858,971,1659,1683]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="262">Structure.</emphasis>
Head
</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[1052,1151,1660,1683]" captionStart="Figs 1–6. 1–2" captionStartId="3.[151,188,1998,2017]" captionTargetBox="[201,1387,195,1963]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[197,1390,189,1963]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 1–6. 1–2 – Concavifer marmoratus Dlabola, 1960: 1 – dorsal view of male; 2– dorsal view of female. 3–4 – Phlepsopsius arabicus Dlabola, 1979: 3 – dorsal view; 4 – head and thorax. 5–6 – Hishimonus phycitis (Distant, 1908): 5 – dorsal view; 6 – head and thorax." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3699262" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3699262/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="262">Figs 3–4</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1162,1220,1660,1683]" captionStart="Figs 7–12. 7–8" captionStartId="4.[151,188,1414,1433]" captionTargetBox="[158,1432,193,1379]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,189,1382]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 7–12. 7–8 – Concavifer marmoratus Dlabola, 1960: 7 – lateral view; 8 – face. 9–10 – Phlepsopsius arabicus Dlabola, 1979: 9 – lateral view; 10 – face. 11–12 – Hishimonus phycitis (Distant, 1908): 11 – lateral view; 12– face." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3699264" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3699264/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="262">9–10</figureCitation>
). Head slightly narrower than pronotum; crown twice wider than distance between eyes, slightly produced medially, sharply angled to face. Gena slightly incised with single fine erect seta near to lateral frontal suture. Lateral frontal suture reaching ocellus and directed mesad of ocelli. Frontoclypeus longer than wide. Clypeal suture arcuate and complete. Clypellus narrower than lorum at base, not produced beyond gena, apical margin straight. Lorum apex widely distant from gena margin, inner margin bordering postclypeus for more than one third of its length. Antenna short, inserted near posteroventral corner of eye, mesal margin of eye entire.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,760,190,1077]" pageId="6" pageNumber="263">
<emphasis box="[181,259,190,213]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="263">Thorax</emphasis>
. Pronotum wider than long, anterior margin convex, posterior margin straight. Scutellum wider than long. Macropterous, forewing veins not carinate, appendix restricted to anal margin, with three anteapical cells, without reflexed costal veins, with A1‒A2 and r-m1 crossveins. Hindwing submarginal vein complete.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,760,190,1077]" pageId="6" pageNumber="263">
<emphasis box="[181,231,383,406]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="263">Legs</emphasis>
. Profemur row AM with AM1, one intercalary row with more than five fine setae gradually reduced apically, two dorsoapical setae, AV with numerous short stout setae, dorsal margin rounded with fine hairs. Protibia AD and PD row each with four macrosetae, AV row with numerous macrosetae gradually increasing in size apically. Mesofemur AV row with stout and short setae, two apical setae. Mesotibia AD and PD row each with four macrosetae, AV row with numerous macrosetae. Metafemur setal formula 2+2+1. Metatibia PD and AD row with long and short macrosetae, three smaller intercalary setae between each pair; AV and PV row with numerous macrosetae extending nearly to base, gradually increasing in size apically. Metatarsomere I shorter than tarsomeres II plus III combined.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,760,190,1077]" pageId="6" pageNumber="263">
<emphasis box="[181,290,830,853]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="263">Abdomen.</emphasis>
Sternal male apodemes parallel-sided, apically angulate, apodeme width equal to distance between each apodeme (
<figureCitation box="[318,397,894,917]" captionStart="Figs 30–40" captionStartId="6.[151,188,2027,2046]" captionTargetBox="[179,1429,1145,2007]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,1135,2015]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 30–40. Phlepsopsius arabicus Dlabola, 1979. 30 – aedeagus, dorsal view; 31 – aedeagus, lateral view; 32 – style; 33 – subgenital plate; 34 – pygofer; 35 – connective; 36 – valve; 37 – apodemes; 38 – female 7th sternite; 39 – detail of ovipositor apex; 40 – ovipositor, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3699270" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3699270/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="263">Fig. 37</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,760,190,1077]" lastBlockId="6.[828,1437,190,1045]" pageId="6" pageNumber="263">
<emphasis box="[181,332,926,949]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="263">Male genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[345,466,926,949]" captionStart="Figs 30–40" captionStartId="6.[151,188,2027,2046]" captionTargetBox="[179,1429,1145,2007]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,1135,2015]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 30–40. Phlepsopsius arabicus Dlabola, 1979. 30 – aedeagus, dorsal view; 31 – aedeagus, lateral view; 32 – style; 33 – subgenital plate; 34 – pygofer; 35 – connective; 36 – valve; 37 – apodemes; 38 – female 7th sternite; 39 – detail of ovipositor apex; 40 – ovipositor, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3699270" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3699270/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="263">Figs 30–36</figureCitation>
). Pygofer long with well-developed macrosetae, ventral margin serrate, curved inside (
<figureCitation box="[159,235,990,1013]" captionStart="Figs 30–40" captionStartId="6.[151,188,2027,2046]" captionTargetBox="[179,1429,1145,2007]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,1135,2015]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 30–40. Phlepsopsius arabicus Dlabola, 1979. 30 – aedeagus, dorsal view; 31 – aedeagus, lateral view; 32 – style; 33 – subgenital plate; 34 – pygofer; 35 – connective; 36 – valve; 37 – apodemes; 38 – female 7th sternite; 39 – detail of ovipositor apex; 40 – ovipositor, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3699270" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3699270/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="263">Fig. 34</figureCitation>
). Genital valve free and with pointed articulation to pygofer (
<figureCitation box="[246,323,1022,1045]" captionStart="Figs 30–40" captionStartId="6.[151,188,2027,2046]" captionTargetBox="[179,1429,1145,2007]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,1135,2015]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 30–40. Phlepsopsius arabicus Dlabola, 1979. 30 – aedeagus, dorsal view; 31 – aedeagus, lateral view; 32 – style; 33 – subgenital plate; 34 – pygofer; 35 – connective; 36 – valve; 37 – apodemes; 38 – female 7th sternite; 39 – detail of ovipositor apex; 40 – ovipositor, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3699270" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3699270/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="263">Fig. 36</figureCitation>
). Subgenital plate with one row of macrosetae near margin and some scattered fine hairs which are short to as long as macrosetae, apical part finger-like, sinuate (
<figureCitation box="[835,913,222,245]" captionStart="Figs 30–40" captionStartId="6.[151,188,2027,2046]" captionTargetBox="[179,1429,1145,2007]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,1135,2015]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 30–40. Phlepsopsius arabicus Dlabola, 1979. 30 – aedeagus, dorsal view; 31 – aedeagus, lateral view; 32 – style; 33 – subgenital plate; 34 – pygofer; 35 – connective; 36 – valve; 37 – apodemes; 38 – female 7th sternite; 39 – detail of ovipositor apex; 40 – ovipositor, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3699270" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3699270/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="263">Fig. 33</figureCitation>
). Style bent, small, finger-like, curved preapically, inner side with projection, well-developed preapical lobe and subapical tooth (
<figureCitation box="[1048,1127,286,309]" captionStart="Figs 30–40" captionStartId="6.[151,188,2027,2046]" captionTargetBox="[179,1429,1145,2007]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,1135,2015]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 30–40. Phlepsopsius arabicus Dlabola, 1979. 30 – aedeagus, dorsal view; 31 – aedeagus, lateral view; 32 – style; 33 – subgenital plate; 34 – pygofer; 35 – connective; 36 – valve; 37 – apodemes; 38 – female 7th sternite; 39 – detail of ovipositor apex; 40 – ovipositor, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3699270" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3699270/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="263">Fig. 32</figureCitation>
). Connective articulated with aedeagus, Y-shaped, branches shorter than half of connective total length (
<figureCitation box="[962,1041,350,373]" captionStart="Figs 30–40" captionStartId="6.[151,188,2027,2046]" captionTargetBox="[179,1429,1145,2007]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,1135,2015]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 30–40. Phlepsopsius arabicus Dlabola, 1979. 30 – aedeagus, dorsal view; 31 – aedeagus, lateral view; 32 – style; 33 – subgenital plate; 34 – pygofer; 35 – connective; 36 – valve; 37 – apodemes; 38 – female 7th sternite; 39 – detail of ovipositor apex; 40 – ovipositor, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3699270" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3699270/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="263">Fig. 35</figureCitation>
). Aedeagus with shaft bifurcate, each branch as long as 2/3 of the total aedeagus length, curved dorsad in lateral view; aedeagus basally with long bifurcate process, pointed at apex, curved dorsad in lateral view, and mesiad apically in dorsal view (
<figureCitation box="[1158,1280,478,501]" captionStart="Figs 30–40" captionStartId="6.[151,188,2027,2046]" captionTargetBox="[179,1429,1145,2007]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,1135,2015]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 30–40. Phlepsopsius arabicus Dlabola, 1979. 30 – aedeagus, dorsal view; 31 – aedeagus, lateral view; 32 – style; 33 – subgenital plate; 34 – pygofer; 35 – connective; 36 – valve; 37 – apodemes; 38 – female 7th sternite; 39 – detail of ovipositor apex; 40 – ovipositor, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3699270" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3699270/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="263">Figs 30–31</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[828,1437,190,1045]" pageId="6" pageNumber="263">
<emphasis box="[858,1045,510,533]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="263">Female genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[1063,1192,510,533]" captionStart="Figs 30–40" captionStartId="6.[151,188,2027,2046]" captionTargetBox="[179,1429,1145,2007]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,1135,2015]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 30–40. Phlepsopsius arabicus Dlabola, 1979. 30 – aedeagus, dorsal view; 31 – aedeagus, lateral view; 32 – style; 33 – subgenital plate; 34 – pygofer; 35 – connective; 36 – valve; 37 – apodemes; 38 – female 7th sternite; 39 – detail of ovipositor apex; 40 – ovipositor, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3699270" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3699270/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="263">Figs 38–40</figureCitation>
). Pygofer with numerous macrosetae. Sternite 7 about twice longer than wide, posterior margin curved, with median U-shaped notch in middle, posterolateral angles acutely rounded (
<figureCitation box="[1341,1424,606,629]" captionStart="Figs 30–40" captionStartId="6.[151,188,2027,2046]" captionTargetBox="[179,1429,1145,2007]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,1135,2015]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 30–40. Phlepsopsius arabicus Dlabola, 1979. 30 – aedeagus, dorsal view; 31 – aedeagus, lateral view; 32 – style; 33 – subgenital plate; 34 – pygofer; 35 – connective; 36 – valve; 37 – apodemes; 38 – female 7th sternite; 39 – detail of ovipositor apex; 40 – ovipositor, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3699270" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3699270/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="263">Fig. 38</figureCitation>
). First valvula slightly convex; second valvula blade-like, abruptly broadened basad of tooth section, regularly serrated with small teeth (
<figureCitation box="[1051,1177,702,725]" captionStart="Figs 30–40" captionStartId="6.[151,188,2027,2046]" captionTargetBox="[179,1429,1145,2007]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,1135,2015]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 30–40. Phlepsopsius arabicus Dlabola, 1979. 30 – aedeagus, dorsal view; 31 – aedeagus, lateral view; 32 – style; 33 – subgenital plate; 34 – pygofer; 35 – connective; 36 – valve; 37 – apodemes; 38 – female 7th sternite; 39 – detail of ovipositor apex; 40 – ovipositor, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3699270" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3699270/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="263">Figs 39–40</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="263" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="6.[828,1437,190,1045]" pageId="6" pageNumber="263">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[828,936,734,757]" pageId="6" pageNumber="263">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dlabola" authorityYear="1979" box="[943,1081,734,757]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Phlepsopsius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="263" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[943,1081,734,757]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="263">Phlepsopsius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Zachvatkin, 1924" authorityName="Zachvatkin" authorityYear="1924" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Pseudophlepsius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="263" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1218,1393,734,757]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="263">Pseudophlepsius</emphasis>
Zachvatkin, 
<quantity box="[927,1003,766,789]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.88696" pageId="6" pageNumber="263" unit="in" value="1924.0">
<quantity box="[927,979,766,789]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.88696" pageId="6" pageNumber="263" unit="in" value="1924.0">1924</quantity>
in
</quantity>
</taxonomicName>
general habitus and 
<taxonomicName authority="Fieber, 1866" authorityName="Fieber" authorityYear="1866" box="[1208,1412,766,790]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Opsius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="263" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1208,1280,767,790]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="263">Opsius</emphasis>
Fieber, 
<quantity box="[1360,1436,766,789]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.73964" pageId="6" pageNumber="263" unit="in" value="1866.0">
<quantity box="[1360,1412,766,789]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.73964" pageId="6" pageNumber="263" unit="in" value="1866.0">1866</quantity>
in
</quantity>
</taxonomicName>
the male genitalia. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dlabola" authorityYear="1979" box="[1020,1157,798,821]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Phlepsopsius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="263" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1020,1157,798,821]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="263">Phlepsopsius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished easily from 
<emphasis box="[883,1057,830,853]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="263">Pseudophlepsius</emphasis>
by the aedeagus shafts not robust and without a projection on the outer side, and pygofer without appendages. From 
<emphasis box="[1030,1102,895,918]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="263">Opsius</emphasis>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dlabola" authorityYear="1979" box="[1118,1256,894,917]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Phlepsopsius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="263" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1118,1256,894,917]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="263">Phlepsopsius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished by the anterior margin of head carinate, transition of vertex to frons forming a distinct angle.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
